Container Image:
(Ansible‑ready managed node)

Containerfile already sets up everything an Ansible managed node needs:
1. Rocky Linux 9 base
2. SSH server installed
   So Ansible can connect over SSH (the only supported transport for Linux hosts).
3. Python installed
   Required for almost all Ansible modules.
4. Dedicated ansible user
   A clean, non‑root user for SSH access.
5. Passwordless sudo
   Allows privilege escalation without prompting for a sudo password.
6. SSH host keys generated
   So the container behaves like a real host.
7. Password authentication enabled
8. Exposes port 22
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
FROM rockylinux:9

# Install required packages
RUN dnf -y install \
    openssh-server \
    sudo \
    python3 \
    python3-libselinux \
    python3-dnf \
    && dnf clean all

# Create ansible user
RUN useradd -m ansible && \
    echo "ansible:ansible" | chpasswd

# Allow ansible user passwordless sudo (optional but recommended for labs)
RUN echo "ansible ALL=(ALL) NOPASSWD: ALL" > /etc/sudoers.d/ansible && \
    chmod 440 /etc/sudoers.d/ansible

# Configure SSH
RUN mkdir /var/run/sshd && \
    ssh-keygen -A

# Permit password authentication (for simplicity in labs)
RUN sed -i 's/^#PasswordAuthentication yes/PasswordAuthentication yes/' /etc/ssh/sshd_config && \
    sed -i 's/^PasswordAuthentication no/PasswordAuthentication yes/' /etc/ssh/sshd_config

# Expose SSH port
EXPOSE 22

# Start SSH daemon
CMD ["/usr/sbin/sshd", "-D"]
